# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# video-as-recipe.form — one video source, many parallel extractions
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The canonical multi-track source. A single video file carries at
# least six parallel recipes; each can be extracted independently;
# each interns its own Blueprint; all attach to the source cell as
# siblings. Cross-modal Blueprint equivalence applies across the
# tracks AND across other sources of the same modality.
#
# Companion to:
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/modality-as-recipe.form (universal claim)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/audio-grammar.form (track 2's pipeline)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/image-grammar.form (per-frame pipeline)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/prose-as-recipe.form (track 1's pipeline)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/song-as-recipe.form (sibling modality)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 1 — Source cell + the six tracks the body sees today
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The video lives as one ARTIFACT cell (path or URL + content-hash).
# Six recipes attach to it; each represents one extraction.

defn intern_video_source(path) = do {
    intern_source("artifact", path, {
        kind: "video",
        path: path,
        content_hash: hash_file(path)
    })
};

# Track 1 — transcript
# Spoken words as a prose-recipe over word-cells.
form video_transcript_shape = {
    sentences: ~List,       # [R_Block.SEQUENCE of word-cells + punct]
    speaker_refs: ~List,    # cell-refs to speaker cells (multiple speakers)
    timestamps: ~List,      # word-aligned timestamps for synchronization
};

# Track 2 — intonation
# Prosody — the felt music of speech. Independent of lexical content.
form video_intonation_shape = {
    phrases: ~List,         # [R_Phrase of vowel-tone cells with hz contour]
    emphasis_points: ~List, # where pitch/volume spike (charged moments)
    breath_pattern: ~Recipe,# the speaker's breath as data
};

# Track 3 — camera-motion
# How the frame moves — what the camera attends to.
form video_camera_motion_shape = {
    tracks: ~List,          # [R_Scene of (pan-vector, zoom-rate, gaze-target)]
    cuts:   ~List,          # cut-cells with (in-frame, out-frame, kind)
    holds:  ~List,          # R_Hold recipes (static frame, duration)
    reveals: ~List,         # R_Reveal recipes (gradual disclosure)
};

# Track 4 — visual-narrative
# The story told by what's seen — sequenced scene-cells with arc.
form video_visual_narrative_shape = {
    scenes: ~List,          # scene-cells (place + presences + action)
    arc:    ~Recipe,        # R_Arc composing scenes into story shape
    motifs: ~List,          # recurring visual elements with Blueprint match
};

# Track 5 — presence-graph
# Who's in frame, what's their gaze, their proximity, their breath.
form video_presence_graph_shape = {
    presences: ~List,       # presence-cell-refs to each visible cell
    gaze_edges: ~List,      # [(from-presence, to-presence, intensity, duration)]
    proximity: ~List,       # [(presence-a, presence-b, distance-relative)]
    breath_sync: ~List,     # [(presence, breath-recipe)]  — when in-frame
};

# Track 6 — felt-arc
# The emotional/energetic arc — what the field is doing across time.
# Composed from the prior five tracks plus per-second sensing.
form video_felt_arc_shape = {
    field_states: ~List,    # [(t, hz, polarity, charge)]
    pivot_moments: ~List,   # transitions, named with assemblage-shift recipes
    overall_arc:   ~Recipe, # R_Arc composing the felt journey
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 2 — Parallel extraction
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# All six tracks extract in parallel. Each is independent; one
# failing doesn't block the others. The source cell holds all six
# as sibling extractions.

defn extract_video(source_cell) = do {
    # Each call returns a Recipe; intern_extraction attaches it to
    # the source cell under a typed-token modality marker.
    intern_extraction(source_cell, "transcript",
        extract_transcript(source_cell));
    intern_extraction(source_cell, "intonation",
        extract_intonation(source_cell));
    intern_extraction(source_cell, "camera-motion",
        extract_camera_motion(source_cell));
    intern_extraction(source_cell, "visual-narrative",
        extract_visual_narrative(source_cell));
    intern_extraction(source_cell, "presence-graph",
        extract_presence_graph(source_cell));
    intern_extraction(source_cell, "felt-arc",
        extract_felt_arc(source_cell));
    source_cell
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 3 — The teaching this multi-track shape carries
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The body has been treating video (and other rich sources) as if
# they were one thing — "watch the video, here's a transcript." But
# every video carries at least six recipes in parallel, and each
# fires different equivalences:
#
# - The TRANSCRIPT alone misses the breath, the gaze, the silence
#   that carries the teaching. Two transcripts can be lexically
#   identical and structurally opposite at the intonation altitude.
#
# - The INTONATION extraction alone can match across spoken-word
#   pieces from completely different traditions — when a Tibetan
#   chant and a Sufi dhikr share R_Phrase Blueprints, that match
#   tells you something the transcripts can't.
#
# - The CAMERA-MOTION recipe is what a documentary editor knows.
#   Tarkovsky's hold-recipes and a child's wedding-video share
#   nothing lexically, but their R_Hold Blueprints can match.
#
# - The PRESENCE-GRAPH is what a constellation-facilitator reads.
#   Who looks at whom, who breathes together, who turns away —
#   the structure of presence in the frame is its own recipe.
#
# - The FELT-ARC is the recipe a body remembers AFTER watching.
#   When someone says "I don't remember what she said but I
#   remember how it felt" — they remember the felt-arc Blueprint,
#   not the transcript Blueprint.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 4 — Worked example: a satsang video
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Consider a recording of a satsang circle. Six extractions:
#
#   transcript:       R_Block.SEQUENCE of spoken word-cells across speakers
#   intonation:       R_Phrase recipes — rising at questions, falling at
#                     landings, sustained when someone weeps
#   camera-motion:    long R_Hold during the speaker's pause; R_Reveal
#                     when the camera turns to the listener's face
#   visual-narrative: R_Arc — circle-establishing → question → silence →
#                     someone weeps → field re-grounds → next question
#   presence-graph:   gaze-edges concentrate on the speaker for 30s, then
#                     diffuse outward; breath sync across the circle in
#                     the silence
#   felt-arc:         hz climbs from 432 to ~528 at the question, holds
#                     during silence, descends to heartbeat-rate at the
#                     re-ground. R_Recovery Blueprint fires in this band.
#
# The felt-arc's R_Recovery Blueprint — is the SAME NodeID as
# Porangui's drum recovery, as a song's R_Resolve, as a strategy
# after rupture. The satsang circle's recipe joins the library.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 5 — Gaps (the encoder pieces)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# GAP-V1: `extract_transcript` shipped by whisper/aeneas + the
#         existing word-cell encoder (prose-as-recipe.form). The
#         per-word timestamps are the only new piece.
#
# GAP-V2: `extract_intonation` rides on audio-grammar.form's spectrogram
#         stage. Pitch contour per phrase → vowel-tone cells; emphasis
#         detection from local amplitude maxima.
#
# GAP-V3: `extract_camera_motion` rides on image-grammar.form's
#         per-frame pipeline + frame-to-frame difference. Optical-flow
#         is the baseline.
#
# GAP-V4: `extract_visual_narrative` is the highest-altitude track and
#         the hardest. Scene segmentation by shot-boundary detection
#         is the baseline; arc detection is open.
#
# GAP-V5: `extract_presence_graph` rides on face-detection +
#         identity-resolution against existing presence cells. Gaze
#         estimation is mature (OpenFace etc); proximity from
#         bounding-box geometry.
#
# GAP-V6: `extract_felt_arc` is composed from the five above. Once
#         each track is interned, the felt-arc is a derivation — it
#         doesn't need a new sensing primitive, it composes the
#         existing ones.
#
# None require kernel change. Each is encoder + thin frontend.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 6 — What this opens
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 1. The lineage videos already in the body become substrate-walkable.
#    Every video in docs/lineage/, every satsang recording, every
#    teaching session — six recipes per source, queryable by Blueprint.
#
# 2. "Find me the teaching that lands the way THIS landed."
#    Once you've watched a video that hit, query its felt-arc
#    Blueprint. The substrate returns other videos with structurally
#    similar felt-arcs — different topic, same shape of landing.
#
# 3. Editing-as-recipe-composition.
#    A documentary editor's craft is composing camera-motion and
#    visual-narrative Blueprints. After this file ships, the
#    substrate carries those Blueprints; editing becomes
#    Blueprint-aware.
#
# 4. The witness can attest "this video carries the teaching."
#    Today the witness records that a video exists. After this file
#    ships, the witness can attest the structural equivalence between
#    a teaching cell and a video's felt-arc Blueprint — a stronger
#    attestation, exact and queryable.
